embeddings.text:
This report summarizes the results of investigations on the absorption, distribution, elimination and biokinetics of 14 4C-BAS 700 F in lactating goats. The test substance was administered by gavage daily on 8 consecutive days corresponding to a nominal dose level of 12 mg/kg feed. Based on the chemical structure of the test substance and the presumption, that the molecule may be cleaved metabolically, the study was performed with two C-labeled test substances labeled in the aniline-ring and in the pyrazole-ring. Two goats were dosed with the aniline labeled test substance and additionally two goats with the pyrazol labelled test substance. 
Body weights were determined at the beginning of acclimatization and application and before sacrifice. Feed consumption, milk production, health and general behaviour were monitored and recorded throughout the study period. Production of urine and feces was recorded once daily, production of milk twice daily in the afternoon and in the morning before application. The animals were sacrificed within 24 hours after the last dose and tissues were collected for radioanalysis. 
No behavioural or physical abnormalities were observed during the study period. Macroscopic examinations at sacrifice revealed no abnormalities. 
For animals receiving 14 4C-BAS 700F (Aniline-label), dosing corresponded to 11.75 mg/kg feed being equivalent to 16.88 mg/animal and day and 11.50 mg/kg feed being equivalent to 16.41 mg/animal and day for goat 1 and goat 2, respectively. 
For animals receiving 14 C-BAS 700F (Pyrazole-label), dosing corresponded to 11.37 mg/kg feed being equivalent to 14.80 mg/animal and day and 11.33 mg/kg feed being equivalent to 14.54 mg/animal and day for goat 3 and goat 4, respectively. 
The total recovery of radioactivity was found to be 85.51 % and 92.25 % for goat 1 and goat 2 (Aniline-label) and 93.90 % and 83.20 % for goat 3 and goat 4 (Pyrazole-label), respectively. 
Urine and feces contained 21.42 and 57.91 % of dose for goat 1 and 26.22 and 60.95% of dose for goat 2 (Aniline-label) and 21.23 and 64.03% of dose for goat 3 and 18.94 and 55.31 % of dose for goat 4 (Pyrazole-label), respectively. Radioactivity recovered from excreta and cage wash amounted to 79.78 % of dose (animal No.1), 87.91 % of dose (animal No. 2), 86.33 % of dose (animal No.3) and 74.60 % of dose (animal No.4) of the total radioactivity administered. Daily recoveries of radioactivity in urine and feces (expressed as percent of the daily radioactivity administered) were in the range of 13.5 - 25.5 and 38.2 - 105.9 % of dose for goat 1 and 18.4 - 29.9 and 23.5 - 127.9 % of dose for goat 2. 
Daily recoveries of radioactivity in urine and feces (expressed as percent of the daily radioactivity administered) were in the range of 16.1 - 28.6 and 31.9 - 78.5 % of dose for goat 3 and 4.9- 24.7 and 25.7 - 69.2 % of dose for goat 4. 
Radioactivity in milk amounted to 0.002 - 0.011 % of dose (from 0.002 to 0.006% of dose in the morning and from 0.004 to 0.011 of dose in the afternoon) and 0.002 - 0.013 % of dose (from 0.002 to 0.003 % of dose in the morning and from 0.006 to 0.013 % of dose in the afternoon) of the radioactivity administered for goat 1 and goat 2, respectively. Radioactivity in milk amounted to 0.004-0.010 % of dose (from 0.004 to 0.010 % of dose in the morning and from 0.005 to 0.008 % of dose in the afternoon) and 0.006 - 0.008 % of dose (from 0.006 to 0.008 % of dose in the morning and the afternoon) of the radioactivity administered for goat 3 and goat 4, respectively. 
Concentrations of radioactivity in milk stayed relatively constant for the 8 application days. Concentrations of radioactivity in milk ranged from 0.003-0.060 - ug Eq/g (from 0.003 to 0.009 ug Eq/g in the morning and from 0.012 to 0.060 ug Eq/g in the afternoon) and 0.002 - 0.043 ug Eq/g (from 0.002 to 0.004 ug Eq/g in the morning and from 0.019 to 0.043 ug Eq/g in the afternoon) for goat 1 and goat 2, respectively. Concentrations of radioactivity in milk stayed relatively constant for the 8 application days. Concentrations of radioactivity in milk ranged from 0.008 - 0.042 ug Eq/g (from 0.008 to 0.021 ug Eq/g in the morning and from 0.020 to 0.042 ug Eq/g in the afternoon) and 0.009 - 0.042 ug Eq/g (from 0.009 to 0.013 ug Eq/g in the morning and from 0.026 to 0.042 ug Eq/g in the afternoon) for goat 3 and goat 4, respectively. 
Organ and tissues (except blood) were pooled from goat 1 and 2 (aniline-labeled 14C- BAS 700F) as well as for goat 3 and 4 (pyrazole-labeled C-BAS 700F). 
At sacrifice, highest tissue concentrations of radioactivity were found in the liver. Residue concentrations of C-BAS 700 F (Aniline-label) in the liver were 0.348 ug Eq/g as well as 0.555 ug Eq/g for samples of 14 C-BAS 700 F (Pyrazole-label). In adipose tissue (pooled fat) and muscle, 0.021 ug Eq/g and 0.007 ug Eq/g were found for aniline-labeled 4C-BAS 700F and 0.025 ug Eq/g and 0.009 ug Eq/g were found for pyrazole-labeled 4C-BAS 700F. 
The levels of radioactivity were 7.327 ug Eq/g in bile for pool samples of goat 1 and 2 (Aniline-label) and 6.557 ug Eq/g for pool samples of goat 3 and 4 (Pyrazole-label). 
With the exception of the Gl-tract, less than 0.5 % of the administered dose could be found in the organs and tissues examined for all animals. 
For further data concerning limits of detection, tissue concentrations of radioactivity and metabolism see report of Project 315778 (BASF SE, Agricultural Center Limburgerhof, Crop Protection Division - Ecology and Environmental Analytics; 67114 Limburgerhof, Germany).
